-- CHRONOLOGY-Key events in the battle for ABN AMRO
-- 
-- Fri Oct 5, 2007 9:18am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/10/05/us-abnamro-takeover-idUSL0566835620071005

 

 (Reuters) - The intense seven-month battle for ABN AMRO AAH.AS neared its conclusion on Friday with a trio of European bidders led by Royal Bank of Scotland ( RBS.L ) set to win control of the Netherlands' largest bank. 

 Following are key events so far in the battle for ABN AMRO: March 20, 2007 - Barclays ( BARC.L ) and ABN outline the plan for a potential merger. April 13 - Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), Spain's Santander ( SAN.MC ) and Belgian-Dutch group Fortis FOR.BR say they have approached ABN, inviting it to talks. April 23 - Barclays agrees to buy ABN in a recommended all-share deal, offering 3.225 shares for each ABN share -- $88 billion at current prices. ABN says separately it will sell U.S. bank LaSalle to Bank of America ( BAC.N ) for $21 billion. April 25 - RBS and its partners propose a cash-and-share offer for ABN worth about $98 billion, if ABN scraps its planned sale of LaSalle. April 26 - ABN investors vote in favor of a motion to break up or sell the bank to maximize shareholder value. May 3 - A Dutch court rules that ABN must freeze its $21 billion sale of LaSalle to Bank of America, opening up the possibility of a rival bid. The next day Bank of America sues ABN and seeks an injunction to block any moves to sell LaSalle to anyone else. May 5 - RBS-led consortium makes an indicative offer worth $24.5 billion for LaSalle, conditional on buying the rest of ABN. May 7 - ABN rejects the RBS consortium offer for LaSalle. May 29 - The RBS-led consortium unveils its bid for ABN valued at 38.40 euros per share. July 13 - The Dutch Supreme Court allows ABN to proceed with its sale of LaSalle. July 16 - The RBS-led consortium improves its bid, offering 38.4 euros per share and raising the cash component to 93 percent from 79 percent before. July 20 - The RBS-led consortium formally launches its 71.1 billion-euro bid for ABN AMRO. July 30 - ABN AMRO withdraws its recommendation of a takeover by Barclays. August 6 - Barclays formally launches its 65 billion euro bid for ABN AMRO. August 6 - Fortis shareholders vote on ABN deal and related 13 billion euro rights issue. August 13 - Barclays gets approval from the Dutch Finance Ministry for its takeover proposal. August 14 - The consortium begins to build a stake in ABN. September 14 - Barclays says it is sticking to the ABN offer. September 17 - Consortium gets approval from the Dutch Finance Ministry for its takeover proposal. September 21 - Fortis and RBS price their rights issue for funding takeover. September 26 - Consortium stake in ABN reaches 8 percent. October 3 - The European Commission clears Fortis' plans to buy ABN's Dutch banking business, with minor divestments. October 4 - Bid by Barclays ends. October 5 - Bid by consortium ends, Barclays concedes defeat and withdraws bid.